metadata.name: In_formation #108
metadata.description:
Interactive features:

1 - Draw a grid
2 - Draw a new word
3 - Draw a bunch of new words
4 - Draw a shape
5 - Change walker parameters 
6 - Change colour palette
7 - Change font
8 - Type a word (4 second window)
9 - Fullscreen
0 - Save Image
Space - Pause

In_formation speaks to the transience of meaning and constant flow and mutation of information and data in the digital era, where thoughts and ideas are rapidly disseminated, distorted, reshaped, repeated and buried under an ever-advancing wave. We find ourselves in a world where clarity is elusive, as meanings are perpetually displaced in an infinite loop of formation and erasure. 

Also, solitaire!

Best viewed in full screen (press 9), either passively (variables will change themselves every so often) or actively by pressing the number keys to draw new things or change variables.

metadata.name: Inland Emotions #215
metadata.description:
Inland Emotions

Over the centuries, ancient philosophers and modern psychologists have come to the same basic conclusion. The fact is that, according to a few millennia of research, there are a limited number of distinct human emotions, predefined by the human psyche. Sometimes it may seem like we are experiencing a "new" one, but on closer inspection, we see that it is the known emotions that are superimposed. Emotions are what they are, and they exist in the same way in each of us, whether we recognize them for what they are or not. But as our history blends into a new emerging state of the world, a whole new range of emotional responses are triggered within us. An infinite maelstrom of variations generated from a simple combination of a few emotions.


Controls :

‚Ä¢ Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

metadata.name: Act One #244
metadata.description:
Act One, where the mannequin says ‚Äútake me home and I will dance for you forever‚Äù.

This work is an exploration of using motion capture data to create digital paintings, and a little belated birthday ballet for #fxhashturnsone. 
20% of primary sales are donated to Three.js.
 
Keyboard Controls:
[P] Play / pause the dance. By default the dance is paused after a few seconds to render a painting.
[S] Save the current view (live mode).
[V] Capture a short webm video (live mode).

Mouse Controls (while dancing): 
[left drag] Rotate
[scroll] Zoom
[right drag] Pan
[right click] Save image

Best viewed in a desktop browser. The output may be different from the preview image if your frame rate is low, reducing the size of the browser window can help improve the frame rate.

Made using Three.js, canvas API and WebGL2.
The 3D model is based on https://sketchfab.com/3d-models/mannequin-dances-ballet-a24678a81a6f4b6d8f8ba0eb1a78e58b, using motion capture data from dancedb.eu. 
Test in Chrome v107.0.5304.107 and Safari v16.1.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 2.0

Created by elsif, 2022.11.

metadata.name: Sano #50
metadata.description:
Using Coronado‚Äôs algorithm as a starting point, Sano extends and embraces the notion of beauty existing in imperfection but allows for more impressionistic compositions with less structure, letting something atmospheric and understated emerge with subtle interactions that combine into dissonant chordal expressions infusing a breadth of emotion while maintaining a characteristic timbre.

Just as Coronado referenced a beat-up vintage guitar that had a patina and sound all its own, Sano refers to the vintage amp it was plugged into. A tube-amp from the 1960s with a spring reverb that when combined with single coils and hollow body of the guitar delivered screaming feedback as well as wonderfully gritty warm tones, which this algorithm attempts to echo visually.

There are 100 artist curated outputs in this short-form collection.

Keys:
S : save at current resolution
1 ‚Üí 6 : save 2000x2500 ‚Üí 12000x15000
(Chrome recommended for higher resolutions)

metadata.name: Bored Computer Screen #681
metadata.description:
"Bored Computer Screen" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022


Bored Computer Screen (BCS) is a direct descendant of Specterüëªpixel‚¨õlatte‚òï, where the central idea is agent and displacement. In BCS, there are agents‚Äîthe small moving circles‚Äîthat get their colors ripped away by the surrounding pixels. Though they occur on the same screen space, they are separated in their own cells, a simultaneous multiverse of sorts. In some iterations, a very clear voronoi pattern will appear. I didn't consciously strive for this look. It's what naturally happens, when you try to divide space, so that the borders occur exactly in between the closest neighbor. When I first saw this pattern emerge, I wanted to see how far I could get the distinct cells to influence each other. The idea that the same algorithmic processes can happen many times but still separately in a single piece has always interested me (and explored in the Infinite Browse series). BCS is an extension of that, albeit a little more chaotic.

Note:
- Best experience on browsers and devices with support for WebGL2 

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5, P5Fbo and perlinjs.

metadata.name: Dump of Links. Part II #98
metadata.description:
Audiovisual generative artwork. It continues with the proposal of the first part, revealing remote points of hills full of abandoned URLs, with a contemplative approach.

A ‚Äò404 button‚Äô shines from above, in the distance, as if it were a star that -possibly- watches over. And below, in a metaphor for pollution, rise islands of floating garbage. As if it were a calm, lonely, suffocating breath, and even sometimes dangerously attractive.

Original sound of voice, piano & synths.

[ s ] -> save 2160x2160px (in live view)
[ f ] -> fullscreen
[ q ] -> stop

Note: This artwork is an animated piece, and requires a powerful GPU for optimal real-time playback. It is important to note that it may not run properly on mobile devices, especially not high-end ones.

metadata.name: Triangular Dreams #29
metadata.description:
Delaunay triangulation is a good old resource in the generative toolbox. In this work I‚Äôve tried to give it a new twist, combining it with different methods to place points in space, and filling each triangle with lines that go from one corner to the opposite side. The goal is to generate a wide range of semi-abstract scenes, that can sometimes be reminiscent of the work of Paul Klee, Lyonel Feininger or other Bauhaus members.

Controls:
[c] to switch between 3 color modes: color mixes, color zones and monochrome
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to save a screen capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at 2x, 3x, ‚Ä¶ your viewport size

This work will adapt nicely to any screen format.
No palettes have been used, it is all random colors within a certain hue and saturation range.
Made with p5.js and d3.js

metadata.name: Many worlds #68
metadata.description:
An interactive chaotic attractor based on a circular harmonograph.

This piece rewards patience.  After the initial structure forms, watch the attractor develop as more iterations are added and the details resolve.  The image will continue to refine itself forever; there is no limit on the iteration number.  Pause, unpause, generate and export jpgs at very high resolutons (see controls below).

This is a generalisation of a piece donated to the Edible East science and art trail on our global sustainable food future, and 100% of every sale and secondary royal1ties will be donated to local food banks.

Controls:  

To stop/restart the attractor iterating, press SPACE.
To switch to a high resolution canvas, press 1-9.  The canvas width will become n*1000 by n*1000 (so 2000x2000 if you press '2') and the attractor will restart.
To export the current canvas as a jpeg, press X.
To update the whole image with current data, press U (helpful if using a high resolution).
To invert, press I.

metadata.name: Aluna #119
metadata.description:
Aluna is the insistence that the world is made and shaped through ideas as well as processes. The series is inspired by the human-led speciation of plants such as orchids and irises, and animals such as goldfish and betta fish - whose features are often exaggerated. Not all speciation is towards ornament - our ancestors developed foods and natural materials through years of selection and hybridization, and this is continued today helping discover new resilient forms. Our ability to imagine and reshape living organisms as well as entire ecosystems is brought into focus through climate change. 

The name Aluna is based on the philosophy of the Tairona people of Colombia, survived through present-day descendants. This Andean philosophy maintains a fundamentally different perspective about the role of humans - occupied with the imagining, enhancement, and nurturing of life.
